## ðŸ§© Use `groups` (recommended for large suites)
Tag tests by importance or type, then run specific groups.

```java
@Test(groups = {"smoke"})
public void loginTest() { ... }
@Test(groups = {"regression"})
public void checkoutTest() { ... }
@Test(groups = {"critical", "sanity"})
public void paymentTest() { ... }
```

Then in your **testng.xml**:
<!DOCTYPE suite SYSTEM "https://testng.org/testng-1.0.dtd" >
<suite name="Regression Suite">
  <test name="Smoke Tests">
    <groups>
      <run>
        <include name="smoke"/>
        <include name="critical"/>
      </run>
    </groups>
    <classes>
      <class name="tests.LoginTests"/>
      <class name="tests.PaymentTests"/>
    </classes>
  </test>
</suite>

Run only those: mvn test -DsuiteXmlFile=testng.xml
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

## ðŸ§© Use `@BeforeGroups` / `@AfterGroups`

You can define setup/teardown logic for certain test groups:
```java
@BeforeGroups("critical")
public void setupCriticalTests() {
    // setup only for critical tests
}
```
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

## ðŸ§© Use Maven or command line filters
You can run only a certain group dynamically: mvn test -Dgroups="smoke"

Or exclude slow ones: mvn test -DexcludedGroups="slow"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

## ðŸ§©Combine `priority` + `groups`
This lets you control both **what to run** and **in what order**.
```java
@Test(groups = {"critical"}, priority = 1)
public void paymentGatewayTest() { ... }
```
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

## âœ… Recommended Strategy (for 1000+ tests)

| Category               | Tag          | Frequency               |
| ---------------------- | ------------ | ----------------------- |
| Critical business flow | `critical`   | Run every build         |
| Sanity checks          | `sanity`     | Run on every deployment |
| Regression             | `regression` | Run nightly             |
| Low priority           | `low`        | Run weekly              |

Example: mvn test -Dgroups="critical,sanity"

